  <text>
    <body>
      <listPlace>
	<place xml:id="Beḍsā">
	  <placeName type="modern" xml:lang="mar-Latn">Beḍse</placeName>
	  <placeName type="modern" xml:lang="mar-Latn">Beḍsā</placeName>
	  <placeName type="ancient" xml:lang="pra-Latn">Mārakuḍa</placeName>
	  <placeName type="ancient" xml:lang="san-Latn" cert="low">Mārakūṭa</placeName>
	  <location>
	    <geo>73.535467 18.720860</geo>
	  </location>
	  <desc>
	    <p>According to Burgess (<bibl><ptr target="bibl:ASWI4"/>: <citedRange>p. 89</citedRange></bibl>), the ancient name of the Beḍsā hill was Mārakuḍa, attested in <ptr target="in:Be1"/>, which he reconstructs as ‘Devil’s Peak’ (Skt. <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">mārakūṭa</foreign>).</p>
	    <p>Beḍsā consists of two major caves, a <hi rend="italic">caitya</hi> and a <hi rend="italic">vihāra</hi>, as well as a small memorial <hi rend="italic">stūpa</hi> and a cistern.</p>
	    <figure>
	      <graphic url="images/Beḍsā/bedse-west1866.jpg" width="400px"/>
	      <figDesc>A map of the Bedṣā cave complex, from <bibl><ptr target="bibl:West18641866"/></bibl>.</figDesc>
	    </figure>
	  </desc>
	  <listPlace type="subsidiary">
	    <place xml:id="Beḍsā-Caitya">
	      <placeName><hi rend="italic">Caitya</hi> cave</placeName>
	      <desc>
		<figure>
		  <graphic url="images/Beḍsā/bedse-chaitya-architectural_section.jpg" width="400px"/>
		  <figDesc>A cross-section of the Bedṣā <hi rend="italic">caitya</hi>, from <bibl><ptr target="bibl:CTI"/></bibl>.</figDesc>
		</figure>
		<figure>
		  <graphic url="images/Beḍsā/bedse-chaitya.jpg" width="400px"/>
		  <figDesc>A plan of the Bedṣā <hi rend="italic">caitya</hi>, from <bibl><ptr target="bibl:CTI"/></bibl>.</figDesc>
		</figure>
	      </desc>
	    </place>
	  </listPlace>
	</place>
      </listPlace>
